{"id": 18297, "date": "1972-01-03T11:00:00", "date_gmt": "1972-01-03T19:00:00", "guid": {"rendered": "http://estreetshuffle.com/?p=18297"}, "modified": "2026-05-10T09:04:35", "modified_gmt": "2026-05-10T16:04:35", "slug": "roll-of-the-dice-natural-magic", "status": "publish", "type": "post", "link": "https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/1972/01/03/roll-of-the-dice-natural-magic/", "title": {"rendered": "Natural Magic"}, "content": {"rendered": "<p>Ah, the summer of 1971: a golden era for fans of the soul side of Bruce Springsteen.</p>\n<p>I&#8217;m far too young to have caught The Bruce Springsteen Band live in concert (I was only three years old when they disbanded), but I seem to turn to those bootlegs whenever summer nears. Something about those warm, bluesy rock and soul arrangements feels appropriate for a lazy, sunny afternoon.</p>\n<p>Today, we&#8217;ll take a listen to one of my favorite original songs from this period: &#8220;Natural Magic,&#8221; performed on at least three occasions but captured on tape only once&#8211;on July 29, 1971 at D&#8217;Scene in South Amboy, New Jersey.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/H9OhTpz87sc?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<p>&#8220;Natural Magic&#8221; may be an original Springsteen song, but it clearly owes a debt of influence to Van Morrison. We can clearly hear the similarities with &#8220;Crazy Love,&#8221; released the year prior.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/OIaKy1vM9hs?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<p>&#8220;Natural Magic&#8221; doesn&#8217;t tread any new lyrical ground either&#8211;mountain high/water wide pairings weren&#8217;t exactly original ideas by that time.</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 40px;\"><em>I&#8217;d climb a mountain if you want me to</em><br />\n<em>I&#8217;d swim the ocean just to get to you</em><br />\n<em>I&#8217;d do most anything that you ask me to do</em><br />\n<em>Don&#8217;t you know now darling, my loving&#8217;s for you</em><br />\n<em>Oh but don&#8217;t take me for a fool</em><br />\n<em>&#8216;Cause it&#8217;d be the wrong thing to do</em><br />\n<em>In the end it sure would be tragic</em><br />\n<em>Because my baby&#8217;s natural magic</em></p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 40px;\"><em>I&#8217;d steal the moon from the midnight sky</em><br />\n<em>Sprinkle him with stardust and tie him in butterflies</em><br />\n<em>I&#8217;d buy for you a sailing ship and I&#8217;d set out on the sea</em><br />\n<em>All I ask of you, darling: you let me be free</em><br />\n<em>And if that is too much to do</em><br />\n<em>To keep my girl from singing the blues</em><br />\n<em>In the end it sure would be tragic</em><br />\n<em>Because my baby&#8217;s natural magic</em></p>\n<p>And yet, despite wearing its influences on its sleeve, &#8220;Natural Magic&#8221; is sweet and charmingly earnest. Together with songs like &#8220;You Mean So Much to Me&#8221; (played just two songs prior that night) and &#8220;She&#8217;s Leaving,&#8221; &#8220;Natural Magic&#8221; represents the beginning of a soulfully romantic vein that Bruce would mine for many years to come.</p>\n<p><img data-recalc-dims=\"1\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" data-attachment-id=\"18552\" data-permalink=\"https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/1972/01/03/roll-of-the-dice-natural-magic/naturalmagic_lyrics/#main\" data-orig-file=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/naturalmagic_lyrics.jpg?fit=512%2C640&amp;ssl=1\" data-orig-size=\"512,640\" data-comments-opened=\"1\" data-image-meta=\"{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}\" data-image-title=\"naturalmagic_lyrics\" data-image-description=\"\" data-image-caption=\"\" data-large-file=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/naturalmagic_lyrics.jpg?fit=512%2C640&amp;ssl=1\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-18552 size-full\" src=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/naturalmagic_lyrics.jpg?resize=512%2C640&#038;ssl=1\" alt=\"\" width=\"512\" height=\"640\" srcset=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/naturalmagic_lyrics.jpg?w=512&amp;ssl=1 512w, https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/naturalmagic_lyrics.jpg?resize=240%2C300&amp;ssl=1 240w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 512px) 100vw, 512px\" /></p>\n<p><strong>Natural Magic<br />\nNever recorded</strong><br />\n<strong>Never released</strong><br />\n<strong>First performed:</strong> July 10, 1971 (Lincroft, NJ)<br />\n<strong>Last performed:</strong> July 29, 1971 (South Amboy, NJ)</p>\n<p>\u00a9 May 19, 2020</p>\n", "protected": false}, "excerpt": {"rendered": "<p>Sweet and slight, &#8220;Natural Magic&#8221; signaled a turn toward more soulful, romantic songs in Bruce&#8217;s set lists.</p>\n", "protected": false}, "author": 1, "featured_media": 68884, "comment_status": "open", "ping_status": "open", "sticky": false, "template": "", "format": "standard", "meta": {"_monsterinsights_skip_tracking": false, "_monsterinsights_sitenote_active": false, "_monsterinsights_sitenote_note": "", "_monsterinsights_sitenote_category": 0, "_jetpack_newsletter_access": "", "_jetpack_dont_email_post_to_subs": false, "_jetpack_newsletter_tier_id": 0, "_jetpack_memberships_contains_paywalled_content": false, "_jetpack_memberships_contains_paid_content": false, "footnotes": "", "jetpack_publicize_message": "", "jetpack_publicize_feature_enabled": true, "jetpack_social_post_already_shared": true, "jetpack_social_options": {"image_generator_settings": {"template": "highway", "default_image_id": 0, "font": "", "enabled": false}, "version": 2}, "jetpack_post_was_ever_published": false}, "categories": [3614, 3], "tags": [1361, 1112], "class_list": ["post-18297", "post", "type-post", "status-publish", "format-standard", "has-post-thumbnail", "hentry", "category-bsb", "category-roll-of-the-dice", "tag-natural-magic", "tag-the-bruce-springsteen-band"], "aioseo_notices": [], "jetpack_publicize_connections": [], "jetpack_featured_media_url": "https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/admin-ajax-58.jpg?fit=1100%2C1100&ssl=1", "jetpack_sharing_enabled": true, "jetpack_shortlink": "https://wp.me/p9w3Lk-4L7", "jetpack_likes_enabled": true, "jetpack-related-posts": [{"id": 27152, "url": "https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/1972/02/01/roll-of-the-dice-magic-kind-of-loving/", "url_meta": {"origin": 18297, "position": 0}, "title": "Magic Kind of Loving", "author": "Ken", "date": "February 1, 1972", "format": false, "excerpt": "Set the wayback machine to almost a half-century ago, and we'll eavesdrop on The Bruce Springsteen Band performing one of Bruce's lost original rockers.", "rel": "", "context": "In &quot;BSB&q